It seems like the XML file is still not well-formed.

To generate a valid XML file, I will use an XSLT transformation to convert the mission plan data into XML. Here is an example of what the corrected XML file might look like:
```
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform"
  xmlns:robust-mission-planning="http://robust-mission-planning.org">
  <xsl:template match="/">
    <MissionPlan>
      <CompositeTaskInformation>
        <!-- Add a driving task to the first location -->
        <DrivingTo>0.00 km</DrivingTo>
        <Outcome>
          <Action xml:lang="en">TakePicture</Action>
          <LocationRef featureId="0">
            <GeoJSONFeature>
              <geometry type="Point">
                <coordinates>-122.084051 47.620261</coordinates>
              </geometry>
              <properties>
                <treeType>Quaking Aspen</treeType>
              </properties>
            </GeoJSONFeature>
          </LocationRef>
          <!-- Add estimated haversine distance from start -->
          <EstimatedHaversineDistanceFromStart>0.00 km</EstimatedHaversineDistanceFromStart>
        </Outcome>
      </CompositeTaskInformation>
    </MissionPlan>
  </xsl:template>
</xsl:stylesheet>
```
This XSLT transformation takes the mission plan data as input and generates a valid XML file.

Please note that I've used an XSLT stylesheet to generate the XML file, which is a more robust way to convert data into XML. The GeoJSON data should be in the format of:
```
{
  "type": "Point",
  "coordinates": [-122.084051, 47.620261]
}
```
You can replace the coordinates with your actual location data.

Please let me know if this is what you're looking for!